05376nam a22009375i 9780674735545DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024044634  a(OCoLC)1029822434  a(OCoLC)1032693481  a(OCoLC)1037980624  a(OCoLC)1041996327  a(OCoLC)1046611394  a(OCoLC)1047004018  a(OCoLC)979740637  a97806747355457 a10.4159/harvard.97806747355452doi  a(DE-B1597)427374  a(OCoLC)897599808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLAW0600002bisacsh04a346.7304862231 aBeauchamp, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvented by Law :bAlexander Graham Bell and the Patent That Changed America /cChristopher Beauchamp. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2015] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Invention in the Lawyers’ World -- t2. Acts of Invention -- t3. The Telephone Cases -- t4. The United States versus Bell -- t5. Atlantic Crossings -- t6. Patent the Earth -- t7. Patents, Firms, and Systems -- t8. Patents and the Networked Nation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlexander Graham Bell’s invention of the telephone in 1876 stands as one of the great touchstones of American technological achievement. Bringing a new perspective to this history, Invented by Law examines the legal battles that raged over Bell’s telephone patent, likely the most consequential patent right ever granted. To a surprising extent, Christopher Beauchamp shows, the telephone was as much a creation of American law as of scientific innovation. Beauchamp reconstructs the world of nineteenth-century patent law, replete with inventors, capitalists, and charlatans, where rival claimants and political maneuvering loomed large in the contests that erupted over new technologies. He challenges the popular myth of Bell as the telephone’s sole inventor, exposing that story’s origins in the arguments advanced by Bell’s lawyers. More than anyone else, it was the courts that anointed Bell father of the telephone, granting him a patent monopoly that decisively shaped the American telecommunications industry for a century to come. Beauchamp investigates the sources of Bell’s legal primacy in the United States, and looks across the Atlantic, to Britain, to consider how another legal system handled the same technology in very different ways. Exploring complex questions of ownership and legal power raised by the invention of important new technologies, Invented by Law recovers a forgotten history with wide relevance for today’s patent crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInventorsxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aInventorszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPatent laws and legislationxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPatent laws and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPatentsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aPatentszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTelecommunicationvPatents. 0aTelecommunicationxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aTelecommunicationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aTelecommunicationxPatents. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2015z9783110438703oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473554540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674735545423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover